## combining the data
path =  "data2"
last_csv = "new_combined_csv.csv"

def get_csv_file(path, last_csv):
    os.chdir(path)
    extension = 'csv'
    all_filenames = [i for i in glob.glob('*.{}'.format(extension))]
#combine all files in the list
    combined_csv = pd.concat([pd.read_csv(f) for f in all_filenames ])
#export to csv
    combined_csv.to_csv(last_csv , index=False, encoding='utf-8-sig')

## convert usertype and gender into ordered categorical types, also bikeid and from_station_name into str

def df_type (df):
    df['bikeid'] = df['bikeid'].astype('str')
    df['from_station_name'] = df['from_station_name'].astype('str')
    df['to_station_name'] = df['to_station_name'].astype('str')
    df['usertype'] = df['usertype'].astype('category')
    df['gender'] = df['gender'].astype('category')
    return df

df = df_type(df)
In [95]:
## handeling datetime features from start_time and  end_time columns

drop_list = ['start_time', 'end_time']
def y_m_d(df):
    df['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['start_time'])
#     df['start_hr'] = df.start_time.dt.strftime('%H')
    df['start_year'] = (df.start_time.dt.strftime('%Y')).astype('int')
    df['start_day'] = df.start_time.dt.strftime('%A')
    df['start_month'] = df.start_time.dt.strftime('%B')

    df['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['end_time'])
    df['end_year'] = df.end_time.dt.strftime('%Y')
    df['end_day'] = df.end_time.dt.strftime('%A')
    df['end_month'] = df.end_time.dt.strftime('%B')
    df.drop(drop_list, axis=1, inplace=True)
    return df
df = y_m_d(df)

Structure of my dataset?¶

I collected the data from many sources as i had data from 2013 to 2020 .. some have different features and some has the same features.

Collected the data with the same features with the function i made above, but it used all my ram and my system errupted as the data was over the 7 million record.. so i had to decrease the data i combine so I used the data for the same year (2019) and collected about 2 million records and i think that should be enough.

after cleaning the data i found it contains 1698725 records and 16 columns the most numerical data that matters are the (tripduration, and age) .. with categorical data in (gender, and usertype) and string data in the rest.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I think the duration, gender, and usertype may affect using this system

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I suppose the age, months, and days can help me explore the data .. as some people might like to ride in certain days and months rather than the others .. the same young people may differ from the elder ones.

## making a cutting function
def cutting(col_name):    
    return pd.cut(df[col_name], bins=4, labels=['very low','low', 'medium','high'])
df['cut_age']=cutting('age')
df['cut_tripduration']=cutting('tripduration')

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Both females and males prefer riding in work days than weekends, and both are more subscribers than usual customers, but males are more bikers than females, although female bikers are mostly younger than male ones.

most of the riders are in the range of 20 - 40 in age mostly distributed in the whole week except the weekend but, thoese who rides in weekends are mostly the younger ones.

It seems also that riders with young age ride in summer than elders that ride in all seasons.

Subescribers are older in age than usual customers, on the other hand subscribers ride in the ordinary work days more than weekends. However, usual customers prefer weekends more.

subscribers as well as customers prefer riding in summer than winter and their peak of riding in (August).

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

female bikers are younger than male ones while both prefer riding in summer than winter, subscribers are older than customers and unlike customers they prefer riding in work days than weekends!

plt.xlabel('Age (year)')
plt.ylabel('Duration (sec)')
plt.show()
